questions.question: The table below provides data on the annual metal production of five countries across three key metals: steel, aluminum, and copper. The Total Metal Output column represents the sum of steel, aluminum, and copper production for each country. Use the data in the table to evaluate the statements that follow.
statements: China produces more steel than all other mentioned countries combined.
Canada's aluminum production exceeds its steel and copper production combined.
Brazil's total metal output is more than a third of the US's total metal output.

questions.question: Six companies—GreenMow, LawnPerfect, TurfCare, FreshCuts, LawnMaster, and YardGuard—offer lawn mowing services across various neighborhoods. The table below provides information on each company for the past month.
statements: At least three companies have a customer satisfaction rating of 90% or higher.
The combined total of lawns mowed last month by companies with 9 or more employees is greater than 220.
Only two companies charge less than $30 per lawn on average.

questions.question: The table below provides data on the number of electric cars owned per 1000 residents in various countries. Additionally, the table also contains approximate population data for each country.
statements: Norway has the highest number of electric cars among all the countries in the dataset
The median of the data in the population column is 50 million
Netherlands has approximately 1.8 million electric cars in the country

questions.question: The table lists the percentage of a city's population that visited a video game store, a movie theater, a nightclub, and a department store in a 3-month period.
statements: The proportion of the city inhabitants in Los Angeles that lives within close proximity to a video game store is larger than that of Miami.
The two cities that spend the most money to promote their department stores are also those in which the night club scene is the biggest.
The proportion of the city inhabitants in Los Angeles involved in the Movie industry is greater than that of any other city listed.

questions.question: Jorge travels to meet once daily with exactly six clients, Clients A through F. When scheduling these meetings, Jorge schedules the most urgent meeting to be the first of the day and then schedules each subsequent meeting according to which client is the least distance from the meeting immediately prior to it.
statements: Client B then Client C
Client C then Client D
Client D then Client A

questions.question: For each of 5 airlines (Airlines 1 through 5), the table shows the percent of flights offered by that airline last year that were delayed by certain ranges of time to the nearest minute and the total percent of flights offered by that airline last year that were delayed.
statements: Airline 2 had the greatest number of flights last year that were delayed by 1 to 15 minutes, to the nearest minute.
Airline 5 had the least number of flights last year that were delayed by more than 60 minutes, to the nearest minute.
Airline 3 did NOT have the least number of total delayed flights last year.

questions.question: The table shows the results of a survey of 1000 households conducted in 1996 and 2006. In 2006, participants were asked to categorize each of 10 products and services as either luxury or a necessity; in 2006, 2 additional products and services were included, increasing the total number to 12.
statements: Exactly one product or service was categorized as a necessity by fewer participants in 2006 than in 1996.
Exactly half of the products and services in the 1996 survey were categorized as a necessity by a majority of survey participants.

Of the products and services that were categorized as luxuries by a majority of the 1996 survey participants, exactly 60% were categorized as necessities by a majority of the 2006 survey participants.
The value of x, representing the range of ratings Don Pizza received, was 4.
Pizza King received exactly one rating of 5.
There are exactly two distinct possible distributions of the five ratings that Don Pizza could have received.

questions.question:
In a research study, each of 15 participants has been given exactly 1 of 15 printing devices. All 15 devices are intended to print a certain image, but each frequently malfunctions and fails to produce the intended image. Each participant has examined data about the past performance of his or her device and has chosen a number of attempts that he or she believes will be the minimum needed to have a good chance of producing at least one correct image. For each participant, the table shows the number of attempts that the participant will make and the actual probability of that participant’s device producing a correct image on any single attempt.

Hypothesis: Every participant has at least an 80 percent probability of producing the correct image within the number of attempts that he or she has chosen.
statements: Participant 6
Participant 7
Participant 9

questions.question: The above table shows, for different cities, the percentage of population of a city which is a regular visitor to different locations in the city. For example: 85% of the people in Atlanta are regular visitors to department stores, and 12% of the people in New York are regular visitors to public parks.
statements: A majority of people living in these cities do not have easy access to a public park.
The proportion of residents that live in the proximity of a movie theater is lower in Dallas than that in Boston and Los Angeles.
The proportion of people who prefer to spend time indoors is greater in Dallas than in Chicago.

questions.question: The table below provides data on the percentage of professions requiring selected protective gear in 2015.
statements: Humans catch diseases from other humans much more easily than from animals.
Ambulance sirens are loud, but they don't damage people's hearing as much as power tools do.
About 10% of janitors earn extra pay for cleaning hazardous areas.
